The paper deals with the identification of nonlinear block-oriented models, which is a topic that falls under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). The paper also proposes a new protocol for determining the location of process noise in the model, which involves analyzing the response of a Wiener-Hammerstein system. This analysis could potentially involve machine learning techniques (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper discusses the detection of certain types of static nonlinearity, which could involve neural networks or other nonlinear models (cs.NE). Finally, the proposed technique is validated on a simulated example and a real-life benchmark, which could involve signal processing techniques (cs.SI).
